{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":34,"record_hash":"sha256:9ab3443de0dbcc181c4a3a71c6ba385fd7be9f23d85c642ee3965b274e050b50","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:16:27.586Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 31687b\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2519\nOutput:\n# Agent Session Handoff Design\n\nThis note describes the current agent-facing read workflow on top of\n`but-agentlog`. It is design context, not a skill file and not an implementation\ncontract.\n\n## Goal\n\nLet a developer continue work from one machine, agent, or provider session in\nanother machine, agent, or provider session.\n\nThe target experience:\n\n1. work happens on a branch with agentlog capture enabled\n2. GitMeta sync moves captured agentlog data with the repository metadata\n3. another machine checks out or switches to the branch\n4. the user asks an agent to catch up\n5. the agent uses GitButler commands to skim prior work and drill down only when\n   needed\n6. the new agent continues with enough context to be useful, without pretending\n   it has natively resumed the old provider session\n\nThis is contextual handoff, not exact provider-native replay.\n\n## Current Surface\n\nThe current agent-facing read surface is deliberately small:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog skim\nbut agentlog skim branch <branch-name-or-ref>\nbut agentlog skim review <review-id-or-key>\nbut agentlog skim change <change-id-or-key>\nbut agentlog show <session-key> [--limit 20]\nbut agentlog show <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--limit 20]\n```\n\n`skim` is the default. It finds every session related to the target and shows\nevery turn in those sessions, in chronological order, with abbreviated user and\nassistant previews. It does not select \"important\" turns and it does not cap the\nnumber of sessions. The whole point is that the agent sees the full turn shape,\njust compactly.\n\n`show` is the drill-down command. It reads exact detail for one session or one\nturn when the skim is too thin, contradictory, or the task requires evidence.\nTurn-level `show` is bounded by default so one large backfill does not dump a\nwhole transcript.\n\nThe old `recap` idea is gone. It selected a subset of turns and risked feeling\nauthoritative while being incomplete. `skim` is b\n[TRUNCATED]\nre model-invoked operations\n- resources are discoverable context\n- prompts are reusable user-controlled workflows\n\nThat maps well to the current shape:\n\n- `skim` is the compact context resource\n- `show` is the explicit read tool\n- a skill or prompt teaches when to use each one\n\nThe lesson is to make the data browseable and bounded, not to force everything\nthrough a generated summary.\n\n### Context Providers And Repo Maps\n\n[Continue context providers](https://docs.continue.dev/customize/custom-providers)\nand [Aider's repository map](https://aider.chat/docs/repomap.html) both show the\nsame pattern: give the model compact orientation first, then let it ask for more\nspecific context.\n\nThe lesson is that the handoff workflow should start with a complete compact\nskim: sessions, turns, counts, agents, branch/review/change hits, and small\npreviews. Full transcript hydration should be an explicit second step.\n\n## Research Takeaways\n\nThe handoff feature should copy these ideas:\n\n- branch/worktree-aware discovery\n- compact outlines before full transcript reads\n- derived summaries as conveniences, not truth\n- stable ids and links across rebases or branch movement\n- reindexable derived stores if we add local acceleration later\n\nIt should not copy these:\n\n- provider-native resume semantics for cross-provider handoff\n- automatic transcript dumping\n- persistent generated summaries as the only source of truth\n- one magic `handoff` command that hides the read path\n- `recap`-style selected summaries as the primary agent primitive\n- cryptographic provenance or SLSA-style ceremony for v1\n\n## Subagents And Compactions\n\nReal data already shows multiple related sessions for one branch. Some are\nsidecar/subagent review sessions, not the main user thread.\n\nThe handoff layer should not hide these. It should make them legible through\nfacts:\n\n- long-running sessions with many incremental turns\n- one-turn review or research sessions\n- compacted or resumed sessions with overlapping context\n- repeated fresh-session tests of the same skill\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:16:27.586Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}